0,11194,11195,11200],{"#text":778},{"person-group":11094,":@":11161},[11095,11096,11108,11109,11121,11122,11134,11135,11147,11148,11160],{"#text":1394},{"name":11097},[11098,11099,11103,11104,11107],{"#text":1402},{"surname":11100},[11101],{"#text":11102},"Zeiger",{"#text":1402},{"given-names":11105},[11106],{"#text":7280},{"#text":1394},{"#text":1394},{"name":11110},[11111,11112,11116,11117,11120],{"#text":1402},{"surname":11113},[11114],{"#text":11115},"Anderson",{"#text":1402},{"given-names":11118},[11119],{"#text":7167},{"#text":1394},{"#text":1394},{"name":11123},[11124,11125,11129,11130,11133],{"#text":1402},{"surname":11126},[11127],{"#text":11128},"Haworth",{"#text":1402},{"given-names":11131},[11132],{"#text":6705},{"#text":1394},{"#text":1394},{"name":11136},[11137,11138,11142,11143,11146],{"#text":1402},{"surname":11139},[11140],{"#text":11141},"Lawlor",{"#text":1402},{"given-names":11144},[11145],{"#text":8249},{"#text":1394},{"#text":1394},{"name":11149},[11150,11151,11155,11156,11159],{"#text":1402},{"surname":11152},[11153],{"#text":11154},"Mortelmans",{"#text":1402},{"given-names":11157},[11158],{"#text":6677},{"#text":1394},{"#text":778},{"@_person-group-type":6337},{"#text":6457},{"year":11164},[11165],{"#text":1326},{"#text":933},{"article-title":11168},[11169],{"#text":11170},"Salmonella mutagenicity tests: IV. Results from the testing of 300 chemicals",{"#text":6349},{"source":11173},[11174],{"#text":6948},{"volume":11176},[11177],{"#text":6475},{"#text":11179},"(",{"issue":11181},[11182],{"#text":11183},"Suppl 12",{"#text":11185},"), ",{"fpage":11187},[11188],{"#text":8961},{"#text":2836},{"lpage":11191},[11192],{"#text":11193},"157",{"#text":6349},{"pub-id":11196,":@":11199},[11197],{"#text":11198},"10.1002/em.2850110602",{"@_pub-id-type":6375},{"pub-id":11201,":@":11204},[11202],{"#text":11203},"3277844",{"@_pub-id-type":6381},{"@_citation-type":6383},{"#text":878},[11208,11209,11210,11211,11212],{"surname":11102,"givenNames":7280},{"surname":11115,"givenNames":7167},{"surname":11128,"givenNames":6705},{"surname":11141,"givenNames":8249},{"surname":11154,"givenNames":6677},[],[11215,11223,11239,11260,11276,12003,14527],{"id":1191,"type":11216,"title":1188,"description":1208,"descriptionNodes":11217,"altText":19,"imageUrl":1214},"Figure",[11218,11219,11222],{"#text":778},{"p":11220},[11221],{"#text":1208},{"#text":784},{"id":2269,"type":11216,"title":2267,"description":11224,"descriptionNodes":11225,"altText":19,"imageUrl":2310},"Heatmap of transcriptome profiling data illustrating co-expressed sets of genes associated with various toxicants, such as genotoxic agents (red side bars). Some agents also exhibit obvious pleiotropy; e.g., chromate induced expression of genes associated with genotoxic agents (red side bars) and genes associated with cadmium and heat shock (blue side bars). This heatmap contains 1,628 genes that were significantly (P \u003C 0.01; t-test) perturbed at least 1.7-fold, relative to the control, by at least one stress agent. The genes in the heatmap were organized by hierarchical clustering with complete linkage based on their error-weighted Pearson distances. The genotoxic (red side bars) and cadmium and heat shock (blue side bars) signatures were identified using coupled two-way clustering. The arrow highlights a cluster of genes responding to ER stress agents thapsigargin and tunicamycin as well as certain other agents.",[11226,11227,11238],{"#text":1402},{"p":11228},[11229,11230,11233,11234,11237],{"#text":2292},{"italic":11231},[11232],{"#text":2296},{"#text":2298},{"italic":11235},[11236],{"#text":2302},{"#text":2304},{"#text":1394},{"id":5077,"type":11216,"title":5075,"description":11240,"descriptionNodes":11241,"altText":19,"imageUrl":5123},"Performance of TGx-DDI with nCounter® analysis system. (A) Heatmap of Nanostring expression analysis using previously tested chemicals; all chemicals were classified as DDI or non-DDI using the same approach used in the DNA microarray analysis. IR designates ionizing radiation. (B) Thirty-eight chemicals were grouped based on mechanistic properties (Table 1); four chemicals that require metabolic activation were evaluated at different concentrations; heatmaps are shown for nCounter® results for each class and prediction results are displayed above. Three methods were used to predict DDI positive (yellow), and the overall prediction (bottom row) is based on positive results with any of these three methods. Published results with CD and Ames assays are shown in the top 2 rows. Yellow and blue indicate positive and negative findings, respectively.",[11242,11243,11259],{"#text":1402},{"p":11244},[11245,11246,11249,11250,11253,11254,11258],{"#text":5099},{"bold":11247},[11248],{"#text":5103},{"#text":5105},{"bold":11251},[11252],{"#text":5109},{"#text":5111},{"xref":11255,":@":11257},[11256],{"#text":1384},{"@_ref-type":1386,"@_rid":1387},{"#text":5117},{"#text":1394},{"id":5702,"type":11216,"title":5700,"description":11261,"descriptionNodes":11262,"altText":19,"imageUrl":5742},"Proposed workflow for applying the TGx-DDI biomarker for genotoxicity assessment of (A) candidates in pharmaceutical drug development or of (B) industrial and environmental chemicals.",[11263,11264,11275],{"#text":1394},{"p":11265},[11266,11267,11270,11271,11274],{"#text":5726},{"bold":11268},[11269],{"#text":5103},{"#text":5731},{"bold":11272},[11273],{"#text":5109},{"#text":5736},{"#text":778},{"id":1387,"type":11277,"title":1384,"description":11278,"descriptionNodes":11279,"tableNodes":11290,"tableFootNodes":11976,"imageUrl":19},"Table","Agents used in the development of the TGx-DDI transcriptomic biomarker (See also Li et al., 2015).",[11280,11281,11289],{"#text":1402},{"p":11282},[11283,11284,11288],{"#text":1406},{"xref":11285,":@":11287},[11286],{"#text":1180},{"@_ref-type":909,"@_rid":1182},{"#text":912},{"#text":1394},[11291],{"table":11292},[11293,11294,11346,11347,11975],{"#text":1402},{"thead":11295},[11296,11297,113